, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Kyme","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from North or South Kyme (Lincs)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":2,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":22,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":32,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":42,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Kyme was born in 1064, in Lincolnshire, England, his father, Sir Simon de Kyme, was 27 and his mother, Lady Rose de Danifer, was 19. He had at least 2 sons with Coates. He died in Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"1064–":"1064–Surnud","1064–1130":"1064–1130","1064–Male":"1064–Surnud","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1094–1162":"1094–1162","1096–Male":"1096–Surnud","1037–1100":"1037–1100","1046–Female":"1046–Surnud","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1064":"1064","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1162":"1162","1094":"1094","1106":"1106","1037":"1037","1046":"1046","um 1096":"umbes 1096","1100":"1100","Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Setby, Lincolnshire, England":"Sotby, Lincolnshire, England"